<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-01-19T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-01-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="627" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d627">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/7732</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by President <persName type="from">Roosevelt</persName> to the Secretary of the Treasury</hi>
                            (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Morgenthau</hi></persName>)</head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-01-19">January 19, 1944</date>.</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>I find a delayed letter from Madame Chiang<note n="46" xml:id="d627fn46">Dated December 5, 1943, <ref target="frus1943China#pg_178">
                                <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1943, China, p.
                            178</ref>.</note> which suggests that the Generalissimo would be willing
                        to send Dr. Kung to Washington. Don’t you think that would be a good idea
                        and that we should accept it?</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>F[<hi rend="smallcaps">ranklin</hi>] D. R[<hi rend="smallcaps">oosevelt</hi>]</signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>